replies.bodyText:
@oraNod I also think this definition is too broad. If we had a definition of "Cache" first, then the definition of "Cache configuration" could be "The specification of a cache".
OTOH it's not wide enough, because a configuration may be defined in a standalone XML/JSON document, as an element in the Infinispan embedded/server XML, or with Java code calling ConfigurationBuilder methods. Also we call a Configuration object a "cache configuration", even if it's not connected to an existing cache, or even registered in a cache manager.
In the end, I think the cache configuration/cache configuration template is a bit artificial right now, and we can't make this distinction as long as the same DefaultCacheManager.defineConfiguration() method is used to define both caches and templates.

@rigazilla Maybe but I'm not sure. What do you think is missing or how should we change the definition?
For me, the "cache configuration" is the thing/artefact you use to enable features and define how you want Infinispan to behave. Which is distinct to a "configuration template" (a thing from which you create configurations). In docs I've seen configuration, template, and definition used inconsistently/interchangeably. Cheers.

@oraNod forgive my delay, I've lost myself on another front.
I would add to the cache definition some more details to narrow down the part of Infinispan that a cache definition controls: i.e. we're going to control/represent a cache resource.
This is what it seems to me that is missing reading the definition.
Anyway @danberindei did a more detailed analysis above :)
